No worries! A struct just groups data, and an impl block puts methods or associated functions. Here’s a quick example:
struct Config { host: String port: u16 }
impl Config {
    pub fn new(host: &str port: u16) -> Self { Self{host port} }
    pub fn set_port(&mut self p: u16) { self.port = p; } }

A struct is just a named collection of fields; it has no special type semantics. A newtype, on the other hand, creates a distinct type that wraps another value (like Box<T>), so 1 == 2 is false and you can have methods and functions specific to the wrapper.

```rust
type Id = i64;
struct NewId(i64);
impl NewId {
    fn new(v: i64) -> Self { Self{v}
}}
```

